erceived and written poetry of Pulitzer Prize winner Jorie Graham. How we read and write on religious matters is transformed by this rare combination of voices in what is surely a unique and important contribution to comparative studies and religious hermeneutics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aChristianity and other religionsxHinduism. 0aHidden GodvComparative studies. 0aHidden GodxComparative studies. 0aHinduismxRelationsxChristianity. 0aVaishnavismxHymnsxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / Theology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478880940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804788809423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804788809.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles